  <p>Carolyn Zagame doesn’t want to be here, at Spontaneous Celebrations, a scruffy community arts center in the Boston neighborhood of Jamaica Plain. She wanders glassy-eyed past the baskets of pronoun buttons and plastic tubs of earplugs and a banner screaming <strong>TEAR THE PATRIARCHY DOWN</strong>, her long down coat zipped tight, praying for the energy to get through this. Normally on a Friday morning she would be puttering at home, chatting on the phone, reading the Bible. But her daughter Ali begged and cajoled for nearly a year, and Zagame finally caved. She can’t deny her daughter anything. That’s why, instead of tending to familiar tasks in her small town on the banks of the Nashua River, Zagame is entering the bubble.</p>

  <h5 class="crosshed">A crosshed here</h5>
  <p>No one quite knows how to talk about the bubble, how to make peace with the idea of it, because bubbles are bad news. Political bubbles, social media bubbles, work and school bubbles, we are in them &mdash; swimming in a sea of sameness, fingers in our ears to block out the noise of competing ideas and uncomfortable truths. But the Ladies Rock Camp bubble is different. To begin with, it’s noisy as fuck, and “fuck,” by far the most popular word here, is generally uttered in unison at high volume to describe the proper response to the status quo. In this bubble, there is no such thing as a bad idea, or a mistake, or a rule. Uncomfortable truths are received with open arms and more Cheese Balls than you can imagine. Everyone here &mdash; and this may be the most bubbilicious thing about it &mdash; is free to be herself. Going back to real life after a long weekend in the bubble can be weird and hard, but it’s also the point: not to keep the rest of the world at bay, but to expand the bubble, to make it bigger and bigger until the whole world is in it.</p>

  <p>But first, rock and roll. Technically, it’s what everyone signed up for. Between Friday morning and Sunday night 43 women, no music experience required, will form bands, learn an instrument, write a song, and perform it in front of a packed house at a nightclub. That’s 72 hours from newbie to headliner. In my long career writing about music, it is among the most punk rock things I’ve witnessed.</p>

