  <p>Some quick transition that gives us the idea that while punk rock is an attitude, it also involves some degree of intention: You have to know what you want, and also how to get there. So in a formal sense, a large part of this weekend is dedicated to instruction - and in the blissful creation of a setting that makes instruction feel like a spiritual act. Pretty much every inch of the community center has been refashioned into a clubhouse/playground/shrine to rock and roll, generally, and female rockers, specifically. The cavernous upper floor, dubbed the Rock Room, is ringed with drum kits and plastered ceiling to floor with photos of female musicians, from Billie Holiday to Blondie to Bjork to Taylor Swift. Every few feet a hand-scrawled genre sign is tacked to the wall: FOLK, METAL, INDIE, RAP, GOTH, GLAM, NEW WAVE, COUNTRY, GARAGE, NOISE, TECHNO, POP, PUNK. Posters in iris-searing shades of pink and yellow have been placed ad hoc throughout the center; there’s one balancing on the back of a sofa, one stashed against a speaker, one teetering on an easel, beaming out the program’s slogans and chants and mission statements. It’s as if a zine came to life and we are spending the weekend in it.</p>

  <hr />

  <p>In the main floor, renamed the Jungle Room, someone has hung a heavy plastic sheet to bisect the space, creating the Bass Cave. Vocal instruction happens in a glorified closet while campers who signed up for keyboard get to hang out in a light-drenched art studio. As far as I can tell this is the only form of injustice at Ladies Rock Camp. The basement &mdash; reached by traipsing through cramped office, descending a steep staircase, and body slamming a meat-locker-style door &mdash; is a warren of tiny, freezing practice rooms. All three floors are bursting with donated gear, in clusters, stacks, and mounds: dozens of amps, cables, drums, pedals, power strips, microphones, Midi controllers, instruments, picks, sticks, cymbal bags, finger tape, everything 85 campers and volunteers will need for a three-day music intensive.</p>

  <p>Except that this isn’t only a music intensive. It might not even primarily be a music intensive. It’s a feminist organization disguised as a music program. They’re not doing this to turn out rock stars; they’re using rock and roll as a vehicle. The idea is to give women (including trans and gender non-conforming participants) an experience that hinges on risk-taking and rewards self-expression and rejects the notion of perfection. An experience like rock and roll.</p>

  <p>And maybe something that puts an even finer point on it? There’s something about the use of music &mdash; the way these women are forced, and are forcing themselves, to do something this difficult and bold and public &mdash; that makes Ladies Rock Camp feel different from the panel discussions and Lean In support groups and Twitter hashtags and other shit we do to make ourselves feel like part of some primal feminist circle. You want something really primal? Try punk rock, baby.</p>

