  <p>That’s the way things unfold at camp: fast. There isn’t much time to stress over details and decisions, thankfully, because while Buchanan is a whiz at running a meeting of engineers- she has had no experience whatsoever crafting an anthem. Half an hour after band formation, the five members of the newly-constituted Girl Skull are huddled in a corner of the Jungle Room having their first Quiet Band Practice &mdash; when groups make whatever progress they can without plugging in. One of their coaches, Buchanan later recalls, started the ball rolling by leading them in “a mind meld mapping thing to figure out what we wanted to say. We had been talking about how few women there are in metal, and the shit they go through, and the common thread was how we don’t want the next generation of girls to have to go through that. One of my bandmates said we need to kick the door open. And I was like, yes. That.”</p>
  
  <h5 class="crosshed">A crosshed here</h5>
  <p>Rock is really dumb, or it can be. Also: coarse, plain, raw, wanton, blunt, and rough. The 10,000 hours of practice we’re told is requisite to becoming a master in any field simply doesn’t apply. That’s not to say there aren’t virtuosic practitioners who make rock music of the highest artistic caliber, only that there are other ways to be great. That’s because in rock there’s one thing that matters more than cunning or speed or experience or precision, and that’s conviction.</p>

  <p>With a little more than 48 hours to go before the campers will be on stage performing songs they haven’t written on instruments they don’t know how to play, Boston-based tunesmith Merrie Amsterburg is in the Jungle Room delivering a laid-back masterclass in songwriting. All you need, she explains, scratching at her guitar, is three chords and a lot of attitude. Heads start nodding. That song is so familiar. Campers are on the edge of their folding chairs. Amsterburg starts singing in her otherworldly soprano.</p>

