  <p>Mancini, who is 48, thought she would be a dancer. She attended ballet class every day after school in her hometown of Syracuse, NY, and fell so in love with musical theater she missed her high school graduation to dance in a production of “Hello Dolly.” Mancini’s parents, traditionalists with an arty streak, encouraged her to follow her dreams but also to be a good girl. A college degree seemed like the smart move. But midway through her sophomore year at Boston Conservatory, Mancini, a rock fan who was spending more and more time in the local clubs, traded her toe shoes for a guitar. What she lacked in know-how she made up in zealotry. She dropped out of school, bleached her hair, and started working at Tower Records, where she met Chris Toppin, another aspiring musician. In the early ‘90s the two women started Fuzzy, one of the celebrated bands to come out of Boston’s alt-rock scene, and Mancini began a serious relationship with Fuzzy’s bass player, Winston Braman. They bought a home and built a life. With an artist named Maura Jasper, she created Punk Rock Aerobics - a fitness regime for anyone who was ever picked last for kickball, according to the companion book.</p>

