  <p>Fast forward 13 years. Mancini is 35. Braman leaves her. “I was freaked out. I knew I wasn’t going to have a baby and a normal life but it felt weird and awful to say goodbye to all that.” Then Jasper split, too, and Punk Rock Aerobics imploded. “It was a really hard time. I was feeling pretty crazy. Then I went to girls rock camp in Portland and it blew my mind.”</p>

  <p>Chance, destiny, karma, call it what you will: timing is everything. As Mancini’s life was falling apart, organizers at the <sup class="article-content__anno-btn" data-anno-btn>Rock ’n’ Roll Camp for Girls</sup> <cite class="article-content__anno-copy" data-anno-copy>The camp grew out of founder Misty McElroy's project as a women's studies major at Portland State University. There are now Girls Rock Camps in <a href="https://www.girlsrockcampalliance.org/">more than 40 American cities</a>.</cite> in Portland, Oregon &mdash; the first of its kind, founded in 2001 &mdash; contacted her about bringing Punk Rock Aerobics to their summer program. So away she went, in emotional tatters, into a community of women who fortified her with the sheer force of their radical support. They wanted Mancini to run assemblies. She said no way. She couldn’t. She didn’t even know their theme song. She would definitely throw up. The night before camp started, Mancini was handed a script and told she would be fine. “85 girls were coming the next day so I did it, because that’s the ethos. I believe in you. I believe in you. I started to be, like, I can do this in Boston.”</p>

  <p>Coincidentally, another East Coaster had travelled across the country to be at the camp: a college student from Somerville named Nora Allen-Wiles, who was doing a summer internship. Under strict orders not to party with the interns, Mancini invited Allen-Wiles to lunch and, despite a nearly two decade age difference, they bonded instantly. The following summer, both returned as volunteers and grew still closer. Mancini and Allen-Wiles were an odd couple &mdash; the seasoned rock and roller and the administrative whiz kid &mdash; but between the two of them they had a full rock camp tool kit. They seriously tossed around the idea of starting a rock camp back home but everyone was too busy, Mancini with two new bands and her vintage clothing store, 40 South Street, Allen-Wiles with her studies and non-profit work.</p>

