  <p>On Saturday, during Loud Band Practice, Zagame and her bandmates in Fallen Petals are working through “My Baby Makes Me Feel Like Spring,” the bouncy retro-pop song they’re writing. The group scored Studio B, the art room, for their practice space, and they’re spread out in a semi-circle, wrestling with the song’s structure. Does it need another section? Should they pause at the end of the chorus? By this time the campers have been to two (of three) Instrument Instruction sessions. LRC curriculum is designed to arm novices with the rudimentary tools to write a part for their song - choose a few notes or chords, make up a melody, bash out a beat - and also explore more sophisticated ideas like using effects pedals and reading tabs, for campers with some music experience. Zagame falls into the first group (so, as it sometimes happens at camp, does every other member of Fallen Petals). She’s learned the basic anatomy of a keyboard, how to turn it on and adjust the volume, and some basic theory, like the difference between major and minor and the moods they create. Each key on her keyboard is covered with a piece of tape naming the notes. She plays three of them in “My Baby Makes Me Feel Like Spring”: C, G, and F. The problem is counting, and she can’t seem to get it straight. “Is it F, 1, 2, 3, 4 or F, 2, 3, 4? This is challenging for me, you guys! I don’t want to screw you up!”</p>

  <p>Despite her reticence to come to camp, Zagame is all in. Cheerful is clearly her baseline, and in a community that skews toward the fluid and the pierced, she is the unlikely life of the party &mdash; piping up, joining in, and dancing up a storm during evening parties in her favorite beige sweater and unironic mom jeans. But while Zagame’s demeanor is jocular, there’s a frantic undertow to her efforts today. “You guys are so cool!” she keeps saying. “I’m just trying to survive over here!” Zagame grabs a tambourine and shakes it over her head. “Maybe your coolness will rub off on me!” The band coaches have seen it before. Saturday afternoon is when things start feeling real, when the fun idea of Ladies Rock Camp morphs into the alarming realization that tomorrow is show day. JC and Mona, Fallen Petal’s coaches, are doing everything they can to be supportive: holding up a giant tablet with the song’s words and chords written in thick marker, loudly counting out each measure, gesticulating at transitions. A couple of instrument instructors, alerted via LRC’s loose but effective chain of communication that someone needs extra help, pop in to offer a few pointers. Practice is almost over and the band decides to play the whole song though without stopping. JC and Mona station themselves on either side of the keyboard, one holding up fingers to count beats and the other calling out the names of the notes. It’s rough going, and not just for Zagame. When they finish, the keyboardist bursts into tears. I’m sorry.</p>

  <p>Saying I’m sorry at Ladies Rock Camp is like quaffing beer at an AA meeting. Mancini has developed slogans and chants in an effort to cure the campers, not to mention the coaches and instructors and administrators and, truth be told, herself, i.e. all of womanhood, of the knee-jerk impulse to apologize for their mistakes, which, you’ll recall, theoretically, don’t exist here. But of course they do, which brings us to Power Pose.</p>

