  <p>When you’re on stage there are gonna be things you’re worried about. We’re gathered in the Rock Room at Saturday assembly. Making a mistake. Am I gonna be good enough? Can I do this? I’m uncomfortable in my body. <sup class="article-content__anno-btn" data-anno-btn>That’s why we’re gonna play Power Pose.</sup> <cite class="article-content__anno-copy" data-anno-copy>A 2010 study co-authored by Harvard University psychologist Amy Cuddy and popularized in <a href="https://www.ted.com/talks/amy_cuddy_your_body_language_shapes_who_you_are">a blockbuster TED talk</a>, found certain physical stances can lead to changes in body chemistry that boost confidence.</cite> Mancini plays this game with the young campers are Girls Rock Camp, too. It comes in handy at all ages. All our lives, whenever we do anything wrong, we’re so apologetic for making a mistake, for taking up space, we’re like ‘Oh my god, I’m so sorry!’ Her voice sails up into ultra femme range on that last part. I do it all the time. I walk out my apartment door and I’m holding laundry and there’s some dude in front of me and I get out of his way and say I’m sorry. But I’m not sorry for living and breathing and walking out my door. How many of you are nervous about making a mistake? Queasy laughter ripples across the room. Yeah. How many of you are nervous about disappointing your band? Murmurs of assent. Of course. We all feel that way. But we don’t care if you make a mistake. We love you when you when make a mistake. If you drop that pick, roll into it. Mancini pulls a pick from her pocket, flings it to the ground, and tucks into an awkward somersault. If you drop a drumstick, jump over your kit. She leaps over an imaginary drum. Boys get that from the start. Go for it, run, fall, scream, spit, sweat. We’re told to stand up straight and get good grades. Her pacing has grown purposeful. More like stalking. I want you to make that mistake bigger. Be our heroes, for our girls and for each other. I want you to find the pose that makes you feel comfortable and good. I don’t care what it is. Stand up.</p>

  {{> modules/newsletter }}

  <p>Although no one could have predicted it, one of the things that makes this high-wire act work is the preponderance of return campers. They are, number one, walking proof of concept. It’s not uncommon to hear them talk about LRC as the thing they most look forward to all year. Sometimes campers come back as volunteers and sometimes volunteers return as campers. Word spreads. Friends tell their friends, who typically resist, because it’s not their thing, they’re not musical, can’t even carry a tune, but the friend tells them it doesn’t matter, not at all, and eventually convince them they’ll be blowing it big time if they don’t take a chance, it’s three days out of your life, so they sign up. On paper, it sounds like serious clique potential. But in reality, return campers scatter like seeds, forming a spidery core that seems to stabilize the emotional and creative chaos first-timers often experience.</p>

  <p>The mission-critical attitude that Merrie Amsterburg talks about in her songwriting workshop, the one that allows scrappy punk bands to take the world by storm, Grace Buchanan has got it. Once Girl Skull stumbled onto the idea of kicking the door open, “I barfed up those lyrics and 15 minutes later we had the song.” For the next two days, “Kick the Door Open (For the Girls Behind)” drifts under the door of Studio D, down in the basement, getting louder and charging harder by the hour.</p>
  
  <blockquote class="bq bq--sm">
    <p>Measure the ankles, the calves, the thighs</p>
    <p>Don’t eat anything that will alter your size</p>
    <p>Don’t be loud, don’t be strong</p>
    <p>If you’re not docile then you’re just plain wrong.</p>
  </blockquote>
  
  <p>A little voice in Buchanan’s head is growing louder, too. It’s her mother’s voice, telling her this isn’t the kind of music she should be singing. “This is her worst nightmare, me in a black t-shirt shrieking in a band,” Buchanan says, and as soon as she realized it “I decided to sing this song for her.” The sounds emanating from all the practice rooms are building, ineffably, not toward something finished or polished, but with a collective energy that feels closer to faith. Remember the levitation game that was popular at children’s slumber parties, where a kid lays flat on the floor and the others place one or two fingertips underneath her limbs chanting light as a feather, stiff as a board, over and over, until the prone body, miraculously weightless, is lifted off the ground? That kind of faith.</p>

