  <p>Even as it deepens faith is tested, as it must be if we’re to recognize its power. Is the body still too heavy to lift? Keep chanting. The self-doubt that Carolyn Zagame figured was ancient history has returned with a vengeance. At practice, she lowers her head and through tears she recites a checklist. “I’m just worried I’m gonna look so stupid up there. I really do like the shadows. I never wanted to be on stage.” She looks ready to bail, at least for a breather, maybe forever, but Zagame agrees to run the tune one more time before breaking to attend one of the afternoon workshops (Rebel Yell Yoga, Conquering the Stage, and DIY Music Creation). Despite the emotional turmoil, or possibly because of it, the players are looking at each other instead of at their own hands while playing, a risk that pays off. The song is sort of hanging together. This is no small feat; everyone is struggling to remember their parts and keep the tempo. As if on cue, a volunteer pokes her head in the door and apologizes for barging in but she was wandering by and just had to tell them how happy the song made her feel. Cheers all around. Zagame steps out from behind her keyboard and gives each of her bandmates a big hug.</p>

  <p>Temporarily restored, she heads off to yoga, but a couple of hours later, between the workshops and dinner, Zagame has another meltdown, up in the Rock Room. It comes out of nowhere. In a flash she’s surrounded by a handful of campers and coaches and someone goes off to fetch Zagame’s daughter, Ali, who joins the huddle. The circle around Zagame grows closer and tighter until it is quite literally unbroken. That night, after Mexican food, there’s a surprise dress rehearsal, when each of the bands performs its song on stage in the Rock Room for what is without a doubt the most adoring audience in the history of rock shows. During Fallen Petals’ performance, Ali is at the lip of the stage with her mouth hanging open, snapping pictures. After they finish, Fallen Petals, like all the bands, exits the stage to ear-splitting shouts of “Holy shit! Holy shit! Holy shit!” and Zagame, looking stunned, falls into her daughter’s arms. It’s been a day. But instead of returning to her hotel as planned, she commandeers the Saturday night dance party. Nobody can believe their eyes when Zagame drops to her knees and launches into an impromptu Kazatsky, the famous Russian folk dance, squatting and kicking with her arms folded in front of her. The room explodes, in shock, in delight, with the knowledge that badasses walk among us, even if we can’t see them. Even if she can’t see herself.</p>

