  <p>It’s show day. Mancini has led a final morning assembly and sent her charges off with eight full-throated, fist-pumping I Rock!’s along with stern instructions to take those words out into the world. A couple of stylists from Miss Laura’s salon in JP have come in to give the campers hairdos and Kelly Davidson, a local photographer, spirits each band away after their final practice to snap promo photos. There’s one more assembly, up in the Rock Room, and one last game, Behind Your Back. Maybe trim if we’re not going to explain the game… As “Total Eclipse of the Heart” blares from the speakers, campers roam the room writing anonymous farewell messages to each other on sheets of paper taped to their backs.</p>

  <blockquote class="bq bq--sm">
    <p>Thank you for being my friend</p>
    <p>You’re a badass</p>
    <p>You count like a MOFO</p>
    <p>You’re smart, fun and kind</p>
    <p>You’re a brave woman</p>
    <p>You are a true artist</p>
    <p>I love you</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p>As the doors to Once Ballroom open to the public, campers pile into the venue’s narrow kitchen, some in glitter and heels, others in jeans and t-shirts, everyone pressed shoulder to shoulder and quivering with nerves and excitement. Mancini and Allen-Wiles jump up onto a metal countertop, crouching to avoid hitting their heads on the ceiling, to deliver the pre-show pep talk. Mancini is beside herself, in rare form, exalting the women for their courage and their heart, reminding them of the extraordinary things she saw them do over the weekend and assuring them that magic is going to happen on stage tonight. She believes so damn hard she could lift up the whole room with her pinkie fingers. But Allen-Wiles delivers the gut punch.</p>

  <p>You can’t forget this. You have to wake up tomorrow morning, even though you’re not putting on your lanyard, you’re not coming back to rock camp, you have to walk back into your job or wherever your life is and say what to the status quo? FUCK YOU. You can’t go back the same. You have to treat women differently. Every day. You have to smile at women on the street. Tell them that you notice them, that they matter, because that’s where it starts. And then you build it and you build it and you build it.</p>

