  <p>Right now, though, there’s nothing to do but play a show. Nine bands are on tonight’s bill, with sounds ranging in style from ethereal noise and swaggering rock to sassy pop and ferocious punk: Unphased, Pity Crush, Nora and the Frustrations, Pink Freud, Together Alone, Fallen Petals, The Sirens, Temporary Goddess, and Girl Skull. If I could I would explain exactly how the exhausted campers muscling through the last band practice at Spontaneous Celebrations turned into the rock goddesses on stage at Once, but Mancini is right. It defies logic. I’m not just talking about the devil-horns hand gestures Carolyn Zagame is flinging at the crowd like she’s the mother of all metal, although that sight alone is worth the price of admission, especially for Steve Zagame, who embraces his wife after Fallen Petals’ one-song set with a palpable mix of surprise and tenderness. I’m not just talking about Girl Skull, Grace Buchanan’s band, whose anthem “Kick the Doors Open (For the Girls Behind)” brought the house down and should be on the radio. I’m talking about swaggering musical performances across the board from baby bands bursting with personality and armed with lyrics that read like pages ripped from a diary, or a manifesto, or a long-buried volume of poetry that might never have seen the light of day if not for three crazy days in a Jamaica Plain community center.</p>

